The paper deals with a consensus protocol for decentralized systems, which is a topic that falls under distributed computing (cs.DC). The paper also considers the presence of Byzantine faults, which is a common topic in computer security (cs.CR). The protocol involves the use of random numbers, which is a topic in both distributed systems and cryptography (cs.DS, cs.CR). The paper also provides explicit estimates on the probability of the protocol finalizing in a given time, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper uses probabilistic techniques to achieve consensus, which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG).
